$1 \le \text{points.length} \le 20$. This is very small.
Coordinates $0 \le x, y, z \le 6$. This is also very small.

Since the number of initial points is small (up to 20), and the coordinates are very small (0 to 6), the total number of possible points is $7 \times 7 \times 7 = 343$. Since the target coordinates are also within this range, this suggests that a breadth-first search (BFS) or iterative level-by-level expansion approach should work, provided the process terminates or cycles efficiently.

